ita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Dacre was born in 1305, in Bradford, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Edmund de Dacre Knight, was 11302 and her mother, Alicia de Towneley, was 25. She married Robert De Bradshaw in 1325, in Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1305–":"1305–Surnud","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1335–1395":"1335–1395","1271–1341":"1271–1341","1280–1308":"1280–1308","1341":"1341","1395":"1395","1362":"1362","1271":"1271","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","Abt 1296":"umbes 1296","1326":"1326","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","Bradshaw, Lancashire, England":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, England","Bradshaw, Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradshaw, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haworth Castle, Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1305–":"1305–Kuollut","1300–1346":"1300–1346","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","1300–1362":"1300–1362","1326–Male":"1326–Kuollut","1335–1395":"1335–1395","1271–1341":"1271–1341","1280–1308":"1280–1308","1341":"1341","1395":"1395","1362":"1362","1271":"1271","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","Abt 1296":"noin 1296","1326":"1326","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1308":"1308","Bradshaw, Lancashire, England":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, England","Bradshaw, Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bradshaw, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Haworth Castle, Bradford, West Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1305–":"1305–Décédée","1300–1346